oncepts that made late-twentieth-century Canadian film legible have been reconsidered or displaced. Canadian Cinema in the New Millennium examines this dramatic transformation and revitalizes our engagement with Canadian cinema in the contemporary moment, presenting focused case studies of films and filmmakers and contextual studies of Canadian film policy, labour, and film festivals. Contributors trace key developments since 2000, including the renouveau or Quebec New Wave, Indigenous filmmaking, i-docs, and diasporic experimental filmmaking. Reflecting the way film in Canada mediates multiple cultures, forging new affinities among anglophone, francophone, and Indigenous-language examples, this book engages familiar figures, such as Denis Villeneuve, Xavier Dolan, Sarah Polley, and Guy Maddin, in the same breath as small-budget independent films, documentaries, and experimental works that have emerged in the Canadian scene. Fuelled by close attention to the films themselves and a desire to develop new scholarly approaches, Canadian Cinema in the New Millennium models a renewed commitment to keeping the conversation about Canadian cinema vibrant and alive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszCanadaxHistoryy21st century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aCaroline Monnet.  aCecilia Araneda.  aDenis Côté.  aDenis Villeneuve.  aDominique T. Skoltz.  aFilm analysis.  aFrancisca Duran.  aGariné Torossian.  aGuy Maddin.  aIndigenous cinema.  aInside Out LGBT Film Festival.  aIzabella Pruska-Oldenhof.  aJay Cheel.  aJeff Barnaby.  aJeremy Mendes.  aKaterina Cizek.  aKazik Radwanski.  aKent Monkman.  aLeanne Allison.  aLindsay McIntyre.  aMatt Johnson.  aQuebec cinema.  aRalph Zavadil.  aSarah Polley.  aSolomon Nagler.  aSonia Bonspille Boi